[Scene: Rebuilt Sea Wall | Dawn]
[Visual: The new concrete and engineered dune stretches like a healed scar along the shoreline. Salt-sprayed bunting flutters; tarps have been replaced by gardens; a ribbon of people gathers at the top.]
[Sound: The ocean beyond the wall thunders—closer, louder than before—then a low communal cheer that rises and falls like breath.]
[Music: Urgent, swelling strings with bright brass—very high energy, celebratory undercurrent]

You stand at the crest of the wall, wind tearing at the loose strands of your hair and the two green streaks at your temple catching like a banner. Your palms are open against the cool concrete; the texture is new and familiar all at once—human hands, industrial mixture, a thousand small corrections sewn into place.

Your breath fogs in front of you. Behind the protective arc of the wall, the marsh sits differently: channels re-cut, planting lines braided into living breakwaters, clusters of engineered roots cradling new seagrass. Here and there, a foundation has been raised; a handful of houses wear new stilts. A few lots have gone to new terraces of salt-tolerant crops. The landscape is altered; not untouched, but held.

Inside your chest, the victory tastes like iron and citrus—sharp, honest. The past months press behind you in a line of faces: Tala's shouted slogans, Rohan's long, low stories of tides, Mateo's patient blueprints, Dr. Park's hard promises and harder reckonings. This is the point where all those lines have been braided into something that holds.

Ivy is beside you, small shoulder pressed into your side, her cheek damp with salt or sweat—it doesn't matter which. She looks out at the water, then up at you, and her smile is sudden and fierce.

Ivy Navarro: "You did it, Akko," (she says your childhood nickname as if to pin you back to what made you brave) "we did it."

You can hear the crowd—neighbors clapping, children yelling names, someone banging a pot. The sound is a drumbeat of very high energy, almost overwhelming. It threatens to sprint your heart out of your ribcage.

You look for Mateo. He is on the promenade, talking quietly with Councilor Nguyen, backlit by early sun. For a second the two of them are unreadable: the planner and the politician, hands moving to the rhythm of consensus-building. Then Mateo looks up and sees you. His face opens—calm, yes, but also astonished in a soft way that cracks the professional shell. Whatever had sat between you in months of hearings and late-night revisions and angry letters is smoothed now into something that says: we carried this, together and apart.

[Visual: Close-up on your hands—callused, ink-stained at the thumb from stopping into your notebook so often. A silver locket at your throat catches a sliver of sun.]
[Sound: A trumpet call—a short ceremonial phrase—cuts through the murmur, then the crowd hushes.]

Councilor Nguyen steps forward, papers in hand, voice amplified.

Councilor Nguyen: "Today marks the opening of Marisma's first integrated protection corridor—engineered structures, community planting, and municipal oversight. It is not the end of our work; it is the beginning of a new way to keep each other safe."

You feel the applause like a physical pressure. The arousal inside you is high—electrified. Every tightened muscle from the council room to this point hums with the aftershock of decisions finally put into earth.

[Scene: Marsh (below the Sea Wall) | Morning — Transition]
[Visual: You descend a set of reclaimed wooden steps to the marsh. Wet soil sponging under your boots; the air is warm and full of the briny sweet smell of growth.]
[Sound: The marsh sings—frogs, the distant slap of water against root, low hum of volunteer chatter]
[Music: Percussive, rapid strings; hope in major key—energetic and bright]

Old Man Rohan waits near a newly installed planting spit, surrounded by a small, ragged cluster of teenagers. His hands are the same rough tools you remember; he moves as if the years between have not worn him down but carved new purpose into him.

Old Man Rohan: "Watch your hands," he tells a boy, thumb pinching a clump of spartina. "Treat it like a boat—gentle when it needs to be, stubborn when it has to be."

There is laughter—the kind that carries relief—and then the teens plant with urgent reverence. Rohan's voice drops lower, and you sense that a lesson is being passed that is larger than plantings: it is memory, craft, presence.

You kneel beside him, fingers in wet soil. Your notebook lies in your bag; you leave it there. For once you do not feel the compulsive itch to record—there will be time later. Right now, the salt and earth and the press of community hands are enough.

Old Man Rohan: "You kept the maps, girl," he says, half-teasing and half-claiming credit. "You put science and people in the same boat. That ain't small."

You smile, and the gratitude spills out sharp and loud.

You: "You taught me how to read the tides. I only learned how to write the models to match what you always knew."

He grunts, a sound that is part pride, part dissent, and taps the earth with his knuckle.

